# Problem Overview

ICRON informed us that our long term capacity forecast results were lacking a set of flights. In other words, they claimed that we did not create capacity forecasts for some flights.

# Approach and Analysis Details

We immediately suspected that the flights were missing from Master Schedule that contains list of flights in the long term.

1. We checked if the flights were actually missing from our results. We checked database table dbo.capacity_forecast_long_term, where API gets our results from. The flights were really missing.
2. Then we checked master schedule from blob storage: datastore-prod/operation/master_schedule. We create forecasts results for the flights in that data. The flights were missing from master schedule, as suspected.

# Resolution and Actions

- We informed ICRON about missing flights in master schedule. They asked us to re-take data. When we took data again, the missing flights were not missing. After we took complete data, we cleared long_term_capacity_forecast task from daily_forecast_dag in Airflow to recalculate capacity forecasts.

# Problem Overview

Customer informed us that they changed a parameter, and the capacity calculations did not change in parallel. They asked for the reason.

# Approach and Analysis Details

The parameters changed were baggage m3 per pax for selected ODs. They picked override from ACRM Capacity Parameters screen (ICRON) and expected baggage_m3_per_pax_source field to change for related flights in Flight Leg Detailed Report screen (ICRON).

We immediately suspected that the forecasts of related flights did not change after the parameter change. This is because we do not send the capacity forecast results if the results (cargo kg and cargo m3) are identical to the latest results sent.

The forecast volume (cargo m3) does not change when baggage m3 per pax changes if it remains zero or if the pax count is 0.

rgo m3) does not change when baggage m3 per pax changes if it remains zero or if the pax count is 0.

We noticed that the flights with aircraft subtype 78I had the same problem. We noticed that we did not create a valid forecast for one of these flights. So, we checked if the aircraft subtype is included in vehicle master. Since the subtype is not included in vehicle master (acrmprod.dbo.vehicle) we could not create valid forecasts and the updated results are not set.

For 6 other flights, we saw that the pax count is 0, due to which the total baggage m3 remained 0 and forecasts did not change. Thus, forecasts are updated but not sent.

Also we noticed that one flight is not sent to us because the flight was not included in acrmprod.dbo.capacity_forecast and acrmprod.dbo.schedule.

# Problem Overview

Customer created a Jira task on THY Jira to inform about a problem in allocation result. ICRON analyzed the problem and found out an inconsistency regarding our forecasts, where the volume forecast is too high for weight forecast.

---

# Approach and Analysis Details

First we controlled if this actually is our result, from database.

After verifying that the results are ours, we have seen that there is only one rate class from the OD:

So, we know that the problem is probably not about rate class enrichment. Hence, going one step back, we analyze any possible problem from day breakdown:

Analyzing day breakdown module output, we realized that the problem is caused by a case from here.

Analyzing day breakdown module output, we realized that the problem is caused by a case from here.

We are subtracting past days bookings from weekly forecasts from current week. Weight, Chargeable Weight and Volume is subtracted independently. Unfortunately, this caused an inconsistency.

---

# Resolution and Actions

We have implemented a fix on the module. We ensured that all CW, Weight and Volume are updated parallelly and consistently. We subtracted weight bookings and using subtraction ratio, volume and CW are reduced, too.

Since ICRON provided a quick fix and informed the customer, there was no necessity for us to give update to the customer.

# Aim

This document gives information about the high forecast problem and the solution of the problem.

---

# Problem Overview

Customer informed us that the forecasts between 2024-09-02 and 2024-10-07 have been high, especially for arrivals in the S&N America region.

---

# Approach and Analysis Details

First, on ICRON, we open the Forecast Accuracy screen under Demand Planning, we checked the overall forecasts and forecasts for arrivals in the S&N America for the departure bucket t-1.

It has been realized that the forecasts are high. To compare with our results, we check the daily_forecast_accuracy table, and the results are the same.

To further analyze, we bring the model information of each forecast from the smart_selection table. Then, we calculated which model accounts for what percentage of the shipments in the t-1 and t-2 departure buckets and its bias for the overall forecasts and the S&N America arrival forecasts.

t-2 departure buckets and its bias for the overall forecasts and the S&N America arrival forecasts.

When we checked the bias, for the long_term_forecast_origin model we saw that 14% bias for the overall forecasts for the t-1 bucket and we saw that forecasts from this model constitute 22.18% of the total forecasts. The similar situation is on the S&N America arrival forecasts. We did not see that this model showed a large bias for the t-2 bucket and that it affected the forecasts much. long_term_forecast_origin seems to be one of the leading models, especially for t-1.

Then, the weekly_enrich_weight table, which is the source of the forecast results, was examined in the model breakdown. We used the actual weights in this table and the prediction values ‚Äã‚Äãin the smart_selection table for analysis.

actual weights in this table and the prediction values ‚Äã‚Äãin the smart_selection table for analysis.

We saw the same situation in this analysis, we saw that the long_term_forecast_origin model gave a bias of approximately 15% in overall forecasts, and that it followed the same course in S&N America arrivals. Then we excluded this model from the overall forecasts and see that our bias is decreased.

In order to confirm that a simulation was performed where this model was left out to see what our MAPE and Bias values ‚Äã‚Äãwould be if forecasts were created without using the long_term_forecast_origin model.

Bias values ‚Äã‚Äãwould be if forecasts were created without using the long_term_forecast_origin model.

Above plot, we can see the original forecasts and the simulated forecasts compared to actual for overall forecasts for t-1 bucket. When we look at our simulation results, we see that they are closer to actual weight than the original forecast results. This suggests that the results could be better if we do not use this long_term_forecast_origin model. This is also observed in the S&N America destination case.

Then the MAPE and Bias checked for overall and S&N America arrivals for the t-1 bucket.

| Overall | MAPE | Bias |
| --- | --- | --- |

| original | 49.49 | -6.23 |

We saw that we had a decrease in bias levels and that MAPEs were greatly affected by this. The results show a large improvement in forecasts when we exclude this model.

For example, for the run_date=2024-09-02 if run_week=1, then the forecasts are for the 2024-09-02 week. If run_week=2, then the forecasts are for the 2024-09-09 week. - Planned Fuel: between 3K and 8KOther metrics may vary as they are R&D-related.

c. In the Capacity Calculation Inbounded Queue and Publisher Queue charts, we expect the blue and pink lines to closely follow each other. If the lines start to diverge, it indicates a potential issue. However, isolated deviations do not require an alert.
